This article is a statement by President Obama on the 55th anniversary of the Montgomery Bus Boycott. The President emphasizes the significance of Rosa Parks' refusal to give up her seat on a bus and how it challenged the nation's moral conscience. He highlights that the boycott marked a turning point in American history, leading to the Civil Rights Movement and the eventual outlawing of racial segregation and discrimination. The President encourages all Americans to honor the legacy of those who fought for justice and worked towards making the country a more perfect union.